│ stop({"edit_points": [[2084, 2085, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue: The assertion failure occurs in `SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup()` when trying  │
│ to remove instructions that were inserted during SCEV expansion. The assertion checks that any instruction being removed should only be used by other instructions that were also inserted during the same     │
│ expansion. However, in our case, the instruction `%iv.1.lcssa2` (which is a PHI node created for LCSSA form) has users in different basic blocks (`vector.scevcheck` and `vector.ph`) that are not all part of │
│ the inserted instruction set.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The crash happens during the cleanup phase of `GeneratedRTChecks` destructor. The debugger shows that `%iv.1.lcssa2` has two users: one in          │
│ `vector.scevcheck` block (a trunc instruction) and another in `vector.ph` block (an add instruction). The `InsertedSet` only contains instructions from the SCEV expansion, but the user in `vector.ph` was    │
│ not inserted by the SCEV expander, causing the assertion to fail.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The issue stems from the order of cleanup operations in the `GeneratedRTChecks` destructor. Currently, it calls   │
│ `MemCheckCleaner.cleanup()` followed by `SCEVCleaner.cleanup()`. However, the memory check expansion may create instructions that use values from the SCEV expansion. When the memory check cleaner runs       │
│ first, it doesn't properly account for dependencies between the two expanders. The correct order should be to clean up the SCEV expander first, then the memory check expander, because memory checks may      │
│ depend on SCEV-expanded values but not vice versa.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): The fix is to swap the order of the cleanup calls in the `GeneratedRTChecks` destructor. This ensures that the SCEV expander  │
│ is cleaned up before the memory check expander, preventing the assertion failure when instructions have cross-dependencies.\n\n5. Conclusion: By changing the cleanup order from `MemCheckCleaner.cleanup();   │
│ SCEVCleaner.cleanup();` to `SCEVCleaner.cleanup(); MemCheckCleaner.cleanup();`, we ensure that dependencies between the expanders are properly handled during cleanup, resolving the assertion failure while   │
│ maintaining correct behavior."})                                                                                                                                                                               │
